The paper deals with routing games and the impact of user diversity on overall cost. This falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT) as well as network economics (cs.NE). The paper also involves the analysis of network topologies and the identification of natural benchmarks, which could fall under information theory (cs.IT) and systems and control (cs.SI). Finally, the paper presents a technical challenge in establishing the "only if" direction of the result, which could fall under machine learning (cs.LG).
